{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17644858","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17644858"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:09:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:09:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18067"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18067","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18067"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.7,0,0.04,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10781"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74928"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10781","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10781"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18067"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60429"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5639"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25135"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25946"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74928"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EVirtue ethics is one of the major approaches to medical ethics, alongside deontology and consequentialism.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the central focus of virtue ethics in medical practice?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Following established ethical rules and guidelines","Developing moral character and professional virtues","Maximising benefits for the greatest number of patients","Respecting patient autonomy above all else","Minimising potential harms to patients"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe central focus of virtue ethics is \u003Cstrong\u003Edeveloping moral character and professional virtues\u003C/strong\u003E. This approach emphasises the importance of healthcare providers cultivating qualities like compassion, integrity, wisdom, and courage rather than simply following rules or calculating outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options represent other ethical frameworks or principles:\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cul\u003E                \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFollowing established ethical rules and guidelines\u003C/strong\u003E represents deontological ethics, which centres on moral duties and absolute rules that must be followed. While rules are important, virtue ethics suggests that good character leads to ethical behaviour rather than mere rule-following.\u003C/li\u003E                        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaximising benefits for the greatest number of patients\u003C/strong\u003E describes utilitarian ethics, which focuses on achieving the best outcomes for the most people. This approach can overlook individual character and the importance of being a virtuous practitioner.\u003C/li\u003E                        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERespecting patient autonomy above all else\u003C/strong\u003E reflects principlism, specifically the principle of autonomy. While respect for autonomy is important, virtue ethics suggests that multiple character virtues, not just respect for autonomy, are needed for ethical practice.\u003C/li\u003E                        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMinimising potential harms to patients\u003C/strong\u003E relates to the principle of non-maleficence. While avoiding harm is crucial, virtue ethics emphasises that good character encompasses more than just harm prevention - it includes actively cultivating positive qualities that promote good medical practice.\u003C/li\u003E        \u003C/ul\u003E            \u003Cp\u003EVirtue ethics asks \u0027What would a good doctor do?\u0027 rather than \u0027What rules should I follow?\u0027 or \u0027What will produce the best outcomes?\u0027 It emphasises the development of character traits that enable healthcare providers to consistently make good ethical decisions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Virtue ethics focuses on the moral character and virtues of the healthcare provider rather than rules or consequences.","The key virtues in medical practice include compassion, integrity, courage, and practical wisdom.","Virtue ethics emphasises being a good practitioner rather than just following rules or maximising outcomes."],"references":["Mandal J, Ponnambath DK, Parija SC. Bioethics: A brief review. Trop Parasitol. 2017;7(1):5-7. doi:10.4103/tp.TP_4_17","Varkey B. Principles of Clinical Ethics and Their Application to Practice. Med Princ Pract. 2021;30(1):17-28. doi:10.1159/000509119"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60429"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18067"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60429","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60429"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-28T12:21:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-28T12:22:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10781"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74928"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attribute